post_text:
It is with great sadness to inform you of the passing of John W. Reavis, Jr.
John was called home early this morning, after hospitalization for a blood pressure problem. He came to Port Chester to become the Director of the Carver Center, and while there he facilitated the move of the Carver Center to the YMCA building. He also served briefly as head of the Council of Community services. He was a sparkplug in the activities of his chapter of Omega Psi Phi Fraternity. He was well known as a community voice during Public Comment sessions at Board of Education and Board of Trustees meetings. Above all, to us, with his years of experience in the field of education and an ability to generate ideas, he was the most effective of our Port Chester-Rye NAACP branch presidents since the late Walter McClain.
No arrangements to announce at this time. There will be a more extensive tribute in our July branch Newsletter, coming soon.

Campaign for Black Male Achievement
June 17 at 7:28 PM ·

June 17th, 1871 - James Weldon Johnson was born.
Johnson co-wrote Lift Every Voice and Sing, which would later become the official anthem of the NAACP.

Interesting Facts about James Weldon Johnson:
- Johnson was also a leading figure in the creation and development of the Harlem Renaissance.
- He was the first African American to pass the Florida Bar.
- President Theodore Roosevelt appointed James Weldon Johnson to diplomatic positions in Venezuela and Nicaragua.
- In 1920, Johnson became the chief executive of the NAACP.
- He was the first African American author to treat Harlem and Atlanta as subjects in fiction, in his novel, The Autobiography of an Ex-Colored Man.
- In 1934 he became the first African-American professor at New York University (NYU)

Video Artist: Committed
#LoveLearnLead

shared_text:
BLACKPAST.ORG
Lorraine Hansberry (1930-1965)

BlackPast.org
May 20 at 12:58 AM ·

Born today in 1930.

“Lorraine Hansberry was one of the most significant and influential playwrights of the 20th Century. Her landmark play A Raisin in the Sun, which opened at the Ethel Barrymore Theatre in New York City, New York in 1959, was the first play written by an African American woman to be produced on Broadway. Hansberry’s account of the struggles of an urban black family was an overnight success, running some 530 performances, and winning a New York Drama Critics Circle Award. It was also earned four Tony Award nominations–Best Play, Director, Actress and Actor. It is generally credited with breaking down the racial barriers to Broadway and ushering in a new era of opportunity for black women playwrights. The play was made into a movie in 1961, with Sidney Poitier and Claudia McNeil reprising their roles and Ms. Hansberry writing the screenplay.”

https://www.blackpast.org/african-american-history/hansberry-lorraine-1930-1965/

Gayle Williams
February 3 at 3:07 AM ·

Timothy Thomas Fortune (October 3, 1856 – June 2, 1928) was an American orator, civil rights leader, journalist, writer, editor and publisher. He was the highly influential editor of the nation's leading black newspaper The New York Age and was the leading economist in the black community. He was a long-time adviser to Booker T. Washington and was the editor of Washington's first autobiography, The Story of My Life and Work.Fortune’s philosophy of militant agitation on behalf of the rights of black people laid one of the foundations of the Civil Rights Movement.

Islip Town Branch of the National Association for the Advancement of Colored People (NAACP) welcomes Jane Elliott to Long Island on Saturday, January 18, 2020.

Jane Elliott will lead a Three-Hour presentation “The Anatomy of Prejudice” in the morning followed by an evening of dinner, trailblazers from across Long Island being honored and Jane Elliott delivering the keynote address.

This will be a historical event that you do not want to miss. The presentation is appropriate for High School Students, School Teachers & Administrators, Elected Officials, College Students, Business Owners, Real Estate Agents, County and Government Workers, YOU!

Tickets are available for purchase via link:

https://itbnaacp2020.eventbrite.com/?aff=FalischaMoss

post_text: Come hear Rev. Anthony Spearman at our branch Freedom Fund Dinner, Saturday, October 12 at 4pm at the PC Senior Center!
shared_text:
T Anthony Spearman
September 14, 2019 at 7:23 PM ·

Delegates to the NC State Conference of Branches NAACP: Over the past two years we have accomplished so much together. There is a wealth of evidence that we have embodied the words in our mission statement, "to ensure the political, educational, social and economic equality of rights of ALL persons and to eliminate racial hatred and racial discrimination." Certainly there have been numerous challenges but they pale in comparison to the victories we have won. When We Fight Together, We Win and when we are "Motivated by the Mission we cannot be Manipulated By the Mess." Please re-elect me for another term.

Friends of the African American Cemetery, Inc.
May 7, 2019 at 12:04 AM ·

You are invited to participate in a Memorial Day ceremony to remember and honor those buried at the Cemetery:

10 a.m., Saturday, May 25, 2019 (adjacent to the Greenwood Union Cemetery)
215 North Street, Rye

As brief background, the land for the cemetery was donated to the Town of Rye in 1860 by Underhill and Elizabeth Halstead with the condition that it “shall forever hereafter kept, held and used for the purpose of a cemetery or burial place for the colored inhabitants of the said Town of Rye, and its vicinity free and clear of any charge therefor…”

If you have any questions or need additional information please call David Thomas at (914) 886-5710 or send an email to afamcemetery@gmail.com

Thank you.

post_text: Branch members Doris Bailey-Reavis, Joan Grangenois-Thomas and David Thomas with Kyle Thomas, attended a reading of the play, "The Kept Private" at Jay Heritage Center. The play tells the story of Andrew Frazier, 95, who applied for pension for his service during the Revolutionary War. A production of the Storyhorse Documentary Theater Co. out of Rhinebeck, NY. Thank you to Suzanne Clary and the Jay Heritage Center, for continuing to enlighten and educate us on our shared history,

shared_text:
WRACTSO
February 16, 2019 at 10:34 PM ·

Recruitment has started for the Westchester Region NAACP(National Association for the Advancement of Colored People) ACT-SO(Acamdeic, Cultural, Technological, Scientific Olympics) Coalition's 2019 Regional Competition to be held on April 6, 2019 at Ossining High School. Visit our website and choose up to three categories from the 31 offered. Do you have a special talent? A passion for writing or citing "spoken word?', Acting or Writing your on play, taking Photographs or making your own Film or maybe you are an "Orator" and wish to cite moving words from Martin Luther King, Malcolm X or President Barack Obama!! Visit our website today. www.wractso.com. Deadline for enrollment is March 16, 2019, Midnight. ACT-SO is an initiative of the NAACP that is designed to stimulate and encourage high school (9-12)students of African descent to showcase their talents and to have the opportunity to go on to the NAACP National Competition in July 2019. For further information please contact Ms. Taylor @ 914-391-5435.🎬🎻🎤🎨🎼🎺🎹🎨🎭🏅
